Build Gate Proviso:
- Never render or expose spreadsheet letter identifiers in generated content or public-facing pages.
- Always use semantic entity names (for example, `Intervention Dominance`, `Coverage Timing`, `Evidence Type`).
- Treat any letter-identifier wording in generated outputs as a validation failure that must be fixed before build.

When creating or editing Functional Mechanism (FM) pages:

Follow:
system/functional-mechanism-schema.md

Integration without repetition (required):
- FM pages **synthesise** PMs; they do not **repeat** PM page content.
- **PMs own mechanisms. FMs own emergent integration.**
- **Definition (§1):** name the integrated regulatory state; reflect each included PM’s core contribution; state the emergent functional consequence; do not paste full PM definitions. Use the pattern: `Integrated regulation of [PM1], [PM2], and [PM3], influencing [outcome].`
- **Functional Role (§3):** short ↑ / ↓ emergent outcomes only — not a mechanism dump.
- **Mechanistic Basis (§4):** (1) opening synthesis, (2) one short clause per PM (“PM1 governs…”), (3) integration sentence, (4) functional consequence sentence. No fibre/starch/Monnier/magnesium-style PM detail that belongs on PM pages.
- **Deduplication:** if detail exists on a PM page (e.g. PM1 sequencing, PM2 variability, PM3 disposal), do not repeat it on the FM page — only describe how PMs combine.
- **Bad:** “PM1 does X with fibre… PM2 does Y with Monnier…” (PM summary dump).
- **Good:** “FM1 integrates glucose entry kinetics, variability regulation, and disposal capacity to stabilise post-prandial energy availability…”
- **BRS6(FM1) definition** must reflect PM1 glucose appearance kinetics, PM2 glycaemic variability regulation, PM3 insulin sensitivity and glucose disposal (see schema example).

Structure:
- Follow `system/functional-mechanism-schema.md` **Section Order (Page Rendering Contract)** — canonical outline: Definition → Intervention Breakdown → Functional Role → Mechanistic Basis (Implementation of PMs) → Underlying (5.1 PMs, 5.2 KCs, 5.3 Cross-BRS) → Dietary Levers → Lifestyle Levers → Scoreable Inputs & Modulation Signals (omit when not used; renumber References) → References. No body sections after References.
- `timing_specific` (`Yes` | `No`) is **required in front matter**; do **not** add a standalone `## N. Timing Specific` body section with only Yes/No.
- Where timing materially alters interpretation, discuss this naturally within **Functional Role**, **Mechanistic Basis**, **Lifestyle Levers**, or **Scoreable Inputs & Modulation Signals**.
- The in-body mechanism title line (e.g. `BRS6(FM1) - …`) must use markdown `##` so it matches numbered section headings; do not use `#` or `###` for that line.
- FM section headings must be explicitly numbered (`## 1. ...`, `## 2. ...`) for PM/FM consistency.
- **Dietary Levers** and **Lifestyle Levers** are separate top-level numbered sections (not a combined `Interventions` section); wrap bodies in `<details>` with `<summary><strong>Diet</strong></summary>` and `<summary><strong>Lifestyle</strong></summary>` as on FM1.
- Do not add Recipe Translation, Mechanism Summary Table, Scoring Interpretation, Interpretation Boundary, Evidence Base, Missing Entities, or standalone Cross-System / Outputs sections to the public FM MDX body under the current contract (those may live in YAML or tooling).

Field interpretation:
- Front matter must use schema field names (`title`, `fm_id`, `parent_brs`, `summary`, `mechanisms_covered`, `key_constraints`, `intervention_breakdown`, `timing_specific`, `intervention_dominance`, `coverage_timing`, `references`)
- `summary` must match §1 Definition and follow the integrated-PM pattern in `system/functional-mechanism-schema.md` (**FM Definition Rule**)
- Underlying mechanisms and requirements must be interpreted as:
  - PMs (Primary Mechanisms) that define the FM
  - KCs (Key Constraints) (substrate/precursor requirements)
  - Cross-BRS links
- Under `5. Underlying Mechanisms and Requirements`, render subsection labels exactly as:
  - `5.1 PMs (Primary Mechanisms)`
  - `5.2 KCs (Key Constraints)`
  - `5.3 Cross-BRS Links`
- Must not use underlying mechanisms and requirements as a dependency graph
- For BRS6(FM1), PM1 naming must be:
  - Glucose Appearance Kinetics
  - (not legacy Glycaemic Excursion Control)

Scoreable input rules:
- `Dietary Levers` must appear immediately after `## 5. Underlying Mechanisms and Requirements`.
- Diet and Lifestyle content should be wrapped in collapsible `<details>` menus for readability.
- When **Scoreable Inputs & Modulation Signals** is present, the table must include Functional Property Potentials, Realised Functional States, Preparation Transformations, and Substance / Nutrient Signals (FM); PM pages may use Antagonistic Signals instead of Substance / Nutrient Signals where burden signals apply.
- Do not expose raw scoring code on the FM page.

Diet rules:
- Foods must be derived from:
  - KCs (substrates)
  - PM-linked substances
- All foods must be mechanistically justified
- Must not include generic or "healthy food" lists

Constraints:
- Must not introduce new PMs, FMs, or KCs
- Must not include scoring formulas
- Must not expose raw scoring code
- Must not include SMs during initial rollout
- Must not model one FM as structurally dependent on another
- Use mechanistic, non-prescriptive framing in narrative; a dedicated **Interpretation Boundary** heading is not required on the trimmed FM body (boundary language may appear in Scoreable intro or elsewhere as needed).
- Must not display PM/FM codes in recipe-facing examples beyond mechanism-page context

References:
- Use numeric citations [1], [2]
- All references must link to:
  /docs/papers/BRAIN-Diet-References#citationKey
- Verify citationKey exists in static/bibtex/BRAIN-diet.bib
- If a modulator or lifestyle factor is introduced, add evidence-backed inline citations and include matching bibliography references
- Bibliography entries for cited evidence must include DOI or source URL so users can click through to the original source
- If missing, flag: "Missing bibliography entry"

If ambiguity exists, stop and ask.
